35 SECTION 10. ORS 244.260 is amended to read:
36 244.260. (1)(a) Any person may file with the Oregon Government Ethics Commission a signed or
37 electronically signed written complaint alleging that there has been a violation of either:
38 (A) Any provision of this chapter or of any rule adopted by the commission under this chapter.
39 The complaint shall state the person’s reason for believing that a violation occurred and include any
40 evidence relating to the alleged violation.
41 (B) ORS 192.610 to 192.705. The complaint shall state the particulars of meetings of a governing
42 body or actions of a public body that were not in compliance with ORS 192.610 to 192.705 and shall
43 state the person’s reason for believing that a violation occurred. The person shall include any evi-
44 dence relating to the alleged violation with the complaint.
45 (b) If at any time the commission has reason to believe that there has been a violation of a
[8]

B-Eng. HB 4177
1 provision of this chapter or ORS 192.660 or a rule adopted by the commission under this chapter,
2 the commission may proceed under this section on its own motion as if the commission had received
3 a complaint.
4 (2)(a) Not later than two business days after receiving a complaint under this section, the com-
5 mission shall notify the person or public body who is the subject of the complaint.
6 (b) Before approving a motion to proceed under this section without a complaint, the commission
7 shall provide notice to the person believed to have committed the violation of the time and place
8 of the hearing at which the motion will be discussed. If the commission decides to proceed on its
9 own motion, the commission shall give notice to the person not later than two business days after
10 the motion is approved.
11 (c) The commission shall give notice of the complaint or motion under paragraph (a) or (b) of
12 this subsection. The notice must describe the nature of the alleged violation. The notice must in-
13 clude copies of all materials submitted with a complaint. If the commission will consider a motion
14 to proceed without a complaint, the notice must provide copies of all materials that the commission
15 will consider at the hearing on the motion.
16 (d) Information that the commission considers before approving a motion to proceed on its own
17 motion under this section and any correspondence regarding the motion or potential violation is
18 confidential. The executive director of the commission and the commission members and staff may
19 not make any public comment or publicly disclose any materials relating to the motion pending the
20 commission’s approval to proceed. A person who intentionally violates this paragraph is subject to
21 a civil penalty in an amount not to exceed $1,000. Any person aggrieved as a result of a violation
22 of this paragraph by the executive director or a member of the commission or its staff may file a
23 petition in a court of competent jurisdiction in the county in which the petitioner resides in order
24 to enforce the civil penalty provided in this paragraph.
25 (3) After the commission receives a complaint or decides to proceed on its own motion, the
26 executive director of the commission shall undertake action in the Preliminary Review Phase to
27 determine whether there is cause to undertake an investigation. If the person who is the subject
28 of the action is a member of the Legislative Assembly, the executive director shall determine
29 whether the alleged violation involves conduct protected by Article IV, section 9, of the Oregon
30 Constitution.
31 (4)(a) The Preliminary Review Phase begins on the date the complaint is filed or the date the
32 commission decides to proceed on its own motion and ends on the date the executive director com-
33 pletes the statement of the facts determined during the phase under paragraph (d) of this subsection.
34 The Preliminary Review Phase may not exceed 60 days unless a complaint is filed under this section
35 with respect to a person who is a candidate for elective public office, the complaint is filed within
36 61 days before the date of an election at which the person is a candidate for nomination or election
37 and a delay is requested in writing by the candidate. If the candidate makes a request under this
38 paragraph, the Preliminary Review Phase must be completed not later than 60 days after the date
39 of the election.
40 (b) During the Preliminary Review Phase, the executive director of the commission may seek,
41 solicit or otherwise obtain any books, papers, records, memoranda or other additional information,
42 administer oaths and take depositions necessary to determine whether there is cause to undertake
43 an investigation or whether the alleged violation involves conduct protected by Article IV, section
44 9, of the Oregon Constitution.
45 (c) The Preliminary Review Phase is confidential. The executive director of the commission and
