10 tations and relevant authorities. Before presentation to the commission, the executive director’s
11 statement shall be reviewed by legal counsel to the commission.
12 (B) Following the conclusion of the Preliminary Review Phase, the executive director of the
13 commission shall attend an executive session of the commission where the executive director shall
14 present the statement of the facts and summarize the results of the Preliminary Review Phase to the
15 commission and recommend to the commission whether there is cause to undertake an investigation
16 or whether the commission should instead dismiss the complaint or rescind its motion.
17 (C) At the executive session, the commission shall consider the recommendation of the executive
18 director and make the final determination as to whether there is cause to undertake an investigation
19 or whether the commission should instead dismiss the complaint or rescind its motion.
20 (D) All case related materials and proceedings shall be open to the public after the commission
21 makes a finding of cause to undertake an investigation, dismisses a complaint or rescinds a motion.
22 (e) The time limit imposed in this subsection and the commission’s inquiry are suspended if a
23 court has enjoined the executive director or the commission from continuing the inquiry.
24 (5)(a) If the commission determines that there is not cause to undertake an investigation or that
25 the alleged violation of this chapter involves conduct protected by Article IV, section 9, of the
26 Oregon Constitution, the commission shall dismiss the complaint or rescind its motion and formally
27 enter the dismissal or rescission in its records. If the commission considers the recommendation of
28 the executive director in an executive session but the commission does not affirmatively vote to
29 undertake an investigation, dismiss the complaint or rescind its motion, the nonaction taken by the
30 commission shall be considered a dismissal of the complaint or a rescission of its motion. The com-
31 mission shall notify the person or public body who is the subject of action under this section of the
32 dismissal or rescission. After dismissal or rescission, the commission may not take further action
33 involving the person or public body unless a new and different complaint is filed or action on the
34 commission’s own motion is undertaken based on different conduct.
35 (b) If the commission makes a finding of cause to undertake an investigation, the commission
36 shall undertake action in the Investigatory Phase. The commission shall notify the person or public
37 body who is the subject of the investigation, identify the issues to be examined and confine the in-
38 vestigation to those issues. If the commission finds reason to expand the investigation, the commis-
39 sion shall move to do so, record in its minutes the issues to be examined before expanding the scope
40 of its investigation and formally notify the complainant, if any, and the person or public body who
41 is the subject of the investigation of the expansion and the scope of the investigation.
42 (6)(a) The Investigatory Phase begins on the date the commission makes a finding of cause to
43 undertake an investigation and ends on the date the commission dismisses the complaint, rescinds
44 its own motion, issues a settlement order, moves to commence a contested case proceeding or takes
45 other action justified by the findings. Except as provided in this subsection, the Investigatory Phase
[10]

B-Eng. HB 4177
1 may not exceed 180 days unless a delay is stipulated to by both the person or public body who is
2 the subject of action under this section and the commission with the commission reserving a portion
3 of the delay period to complete its actions.
4 (b) During the Investigatory Phase, the commission may seek any additional information, ad-
5 minister oaths, take depositions and issue subpoenas to compel attendance of witnesses and the
6 production of books, papers, records, memoranda or other information necessary to complete the
7 investigation. If any person fails to comply with any subpoena issued under this paragraph or refuses
8 to testify on any matters on which the person may be lawfully interrogated, the commission shall
9 follow the procedure described in ORS 183.440 to compel compliance.
10 (c) The time limit imposed in this subsection and the commission’s investigation:
11 (A) May be suspended if there is a pending criminal investigation that relates to the issues
12 arising out of the underlying facts or conduct at issue in the matter before the commission and the
13 commission determines that it cannot adequately complete its investigation until the pending crimi-
14 nal investigation is complete;
15 (B) May be suspended if a suit is commenced under ORS 192.680 concerning the same meetings
16 of a governing body that are the subject of the investigation by the commission, until a final adju-
17 dication of the suit has been made; or
18 (C) Are suspended if a court has enjoined the commission from continuing its investigation.
19 (d) At the end of the Investigatory Phase, the commission shall take action by order. The action
20 may include:
21 (A) Dismissal, with or without comment;
22 (B) Continuation of the investigation for a period not to exceed 30 days for the purpose of ad-
23 ditional fact-finding;
24 (C) Moving to a contested case proceeding;
25 (D) Entering into a negotiated settlement; or
26 (E) Taking other appropriate action if justified by the findings.
27 (e) The commission may move to a contested case proceeding if the commission determines that
28 the information presented to the commission is sufficient to make a preliminary finding of:
29 (A) A violation of any provision of this chapter or of any rule adopted by the commission under
30 this chapter; or
31 (B) A violation of any provision of ORS 192.610 to 192.705.
32 (7) A person conducting any inquiry or investigation under this section shall:
33 (a) Conduct the inquiry or investigation in an impartial and objective manner; and
34 (b) Provide to the executive director or the commission all favorable and unfavorable informa-
35 tion the person collects.
36 (8) The commission shall report the findings of any inquiry or investigation in an impartial
37 manner. The commission shall report both favorable and unfavorable findings and shall make the
38 findings available to:
39 (a) The person, governing body or public body who is the subject of the inquiry or investi-
40 gation;
41 (b) The appointing authority, if any;
42 (c) The Attorney General, if the findings relate to a state public official;
43 (d) The appropriate district attorney, if the findings relate to a local public official;
44 (e) The Commission on Judicial Fitness and Disability, if the findings relate to a judge; and
45 (f) The governing body of a public body, if the inquiry or investigation concerns an alleged vi-
[11]

B-Eng. HB 4177
1 olation of ORS 192.610 to 192.705 and the person who is the subject of the inquiry or investigation
2 is a member of that governing body.
3 (9) Hearings conducted under this chapter must be held before an administrative law judge as-
4 signed from the Office of Administrative Hearings established under ORS 183.605. The procedure
5 shall be that for a contested case under ORS chapter 183.
6 (10) The Oregon Government Ethics Commission may not inquire into or investigate any conduct
7 that occurred more than four years before a complaint is filed or a motion is approved under sub-
8 section (1) of this section.
9 (11) This section does not prevent the commission and the person or public body alleged to have
10 violated any provision of this chapter or ORS 192.660 or any rule adopted by the commission under
11 this chapter from stipulating to a finding of fact concerning the violation and consenting to an ap-
12 propriate penalty. The commission shall enter an order based on the stipulation and consent.
13 (12) At any time during proceedings conducted under this section, the commission may enter
14 into a negotiated settlement with the person or public body who is the subject of action under this
15 section.
16 (13) As used in this section:
17 (a) “Cause” means that there is a substantial, objective basis for believing that an offense or
18 violation may have been committed and the person who is the subject of an inquiry may have com-
19 mitted the offense or violation.
20 (b) “Governing body” has the meaning given that term in ORS 192.610.
21 (c) “Pending” means that a prosecuting attorney is either actively investigating the factual basis
22 of the alleged criminal conduct, is preparing to seek or is seeking an accusatory instrument, has
23 obtained an accusatory instrument and is proceeding to trial or is in trial or in the process of ne-
24 gotiating a plea.
25 SECTION 11. ORS 244.350 is amended to read:
26 244.350. (1) The Oregon Government Ethics Commission may impose civil penalties not to ex-
27 ceed:
28 (a) Except as provided in paragraphs (b), (c) and (d) of this subsection, $5,000 for violation of
29 any provision of this chapter or any resolution adopted under ORS 244.160.
30 (b) $25,000 for violation of ORS 244.045.
31 (c) $10,000 for willfully violating ORS 244.040.
32 (d) Two times the amount of the penalty provision for violating a nondisclosure agreement that
33 is contained within each nondisclosure agreement entered into in violation of ORS 244.049.
34 (2)(a) Except as provided in paragraph (b) of this subsection, the commission may impose civil
35 penalties not to exceed $1,000 for violation of any provision of ORS 192.610 to 192.705.
36 (b) A civil penalty may not be imposed under this subsection if the violation occurred as a result
37 of the public body or the governing body of the public body acting upon the advice of the public
38 body’s counsel.
39 (3) The commission may impose civil penalties not to exceed $250 for violation of ORS 293.708.
40 A civil penalty imposed under this subsection is in addition to and not in lieu of a civil penalty that
41 may be imposed under subsection (1) of this section.
42 (4)(a) The commission may impose civil penalties on a person who fails to file the statement
43 required under ORS 244.050 or 244.217. In enforcing this subsection, the commission is not required
44 to follow the procedures in ORS 244.260 before finding that a violation of ORS 244.050 or 244.217
45 has occurred.
[12]

B-Eng. HB 4177
1 (b) Failure to file the required statement in timely fashion is prima facie evidence of a violation
2 of ORS 244.050 or 244.217.
3 (c) The commission may impose a civil penalty of $10 for each of the first 14 days the statement
4 is late beyond the date set by law, or by the commission under ORS 244.050, and $50 for each day
5 thereafter. The maximum penalty that may be imposed under this subsection is $5,000.
6 (5) In lieu of or in conjunction with finding a violation of law or any resolution or imposing a
7 civil penalty under this section, the commission may issue a written letter of reprimand, explanation
8 or education.
9 (6)(a) A civil penalty imposed under this section against a public official for a violation of ORS
10 192.610 to 192.705 is a personal liability of each member of the governing body on whom the penalty
11 is imposed and may not be paid for or indemnified by the governing body or public body that the
12 member is associated with.
13 (b) A civil penalty imposed against a public body under this section for a violation of ORS
14 192.610 to 192.705 is a liability of the public body against whom the penalty is imposed and
15 shall be paid by the public body.
16 (c) Notwithstanding paragraph (a) of this subsection, a civil penalty imposed under this
17 section for an administrative error that amounts to a violation of ORS 192.610 to 192.705 is
18 a liability of the public body and may not be paid for by a public official associated with the
19 public body.
20 [(b)] (d) As used in this subsection, “governing body” and “public body” have the meanings given
21 those terms in ORS 192.610.
22 SECTION 12. In addition to and not in lieu of any other appropriation, there is appro-
23 priated to the Oregon Government Ethics Commission, for the biennium ending June 30,
24 2027, out of the General Fund, the amount of $325,950 to carry out the amendments to ORS
25 192.610, 192.630, 192.640, 192.650, 192.670, 192.685, 192.690, 192.700, 192.705, 244.260 and 244.350
26 by sections 1 to 11 of this 2026 Act.
27 SECTION 13. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
28 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
